{"title_page": "Jack Armstrong (basketball)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Jack Armstrong\n| image = 1_matt_devlin_jack_armstrong_2019.jpg\n| caption = Armstrong (right) with [[Matt Devlin (sportscaster)|Matt Devlin]] at Game 2 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]\n| birth_name = John Joseph Armstrong\n| birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1963|1|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation = [[Sportscaster]]\n| networth = \n|alma_mater =[[Fordham University]]\n| employer = [[Bell Media]]\n| spouse = Dena Armstrong\n| children = Brian Armstrong, Kevin Armstrong, Tim Armstrong\n| website = \n}}\n'''John Joseph \"Jack\" Armstrong''' (born January 3, 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/coaches/jack-armstrong-1.html|title=Jack Armstrong Coaching Record - College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref> is an American [[sportscaster]], working primarily for the [[Toronto Raptors]] on [[The Sports Network|TSN]] and [[NBA TV Canada]]. Armstrong is also the college basketball analyst for [[The Sports Network|TSN]]. \n\n==Personal==\nJack is the son of Irish immigrants. He has three brothers, William, James and Brendan. Jack's father died when Jack was age seven and his mother Mary raised him alone.<ref name=\"tgm\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/article-raptors-broadcaster-jack-armstrong-father-to-three-adopted-sons/ |title=Raptors broadcaster Jack Armstrong, father to three adopted sons, calls parenting \u2018an amazing gift\u2019 |first=Lori |last=Ewing |date=October 15, 2018 |work=The Globe and Mail |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref> Armstrong graduated from [[Fordham University]] in 1985 with a Masters in Communication.<ref>{{cite web |work=Fordham Alumni |url=https://fordhamsports.com/news/2014/12/21/GEN_1221142243.aspx |title=Alumni RAMblings - Jack Armstrong |date=December 21, 2014 |accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJack is married to Dena Armstrong, who  was the women's soccer coach at Niagara University. They met at Niagara University, when they were both coaches. They are the parents of three adopted sons.<ref name=\"tgm\"/> They live in [[Lewiston, New York]] just across the Niagara River from Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/basketball/nba/20-questions-toronto-raptors-broadcaster-jack-armstrong-on-being-happy-the-all-consuming-stress-of-coaching-and-the-vince-carter-era |title=20 Questions: Toronto Raptors broadcaster Jack Armstrong on being happy, the 'all-consuming' stress of coaching and the Vince Carter era |date=January 8, 2015 |work=The National Post |accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nFrom 1989 to 1998, Armstrong was the lead basketball coach of [[Niagara University]]. In the 1992\u201393 season, he led the [[Niagara Purple Eagles men's basketball|Niagara Purple Eagles]] to a 23\u20137 record and was named the New York State Division I Coach of the Year. His overall record with the team was 100-154.<ref name=buff /> \n\n==Broadcast career==\nArmstrong is currently an NBA analyst for [[The Sports Network|TSN]] and the on-air in-game broadcaster for the [[Toronto Raptors]] NBA team.<ref name=\"tgm\"/> He has been a part of the broadcast team since 2000.<ref name=buff>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2015/07/17/jack-armstrong-is-going-strong-as-broadcast-analyst-for-the-toronto-raptors/|title=Jack Armstrong is going strong as broadcast analyst for the Toronto Raptors|date=July 17, 2015}}</ref> Armstrong has two catch-phrases that he uses during game broadcasts: \"Helloooo\" and \"Get that garbage outta here\".<ref name=\"tgm\"/> The \"get that garbage outta here\" phrase was also used by Armstrong in commercials for the [[City of Toronto government]] to encourage keeping garbage out of recycling materials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.ca/services-payments/recycling-organics-garbage/houses/what-goes-in-my-blue-bin/ |title=What Goes in the Blue Bin? |publisher=City of Toronto |accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nArmstrong is a 3 time winner of the [[Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] for Best Sports Analyst in a Sports Program or Series.\n\nOn Thursday, July 31, 2008, it was announced that Jack Armstrong would take over ''[[The Chuck Swirsky Show]]'' effective August 18, 2008, alongside [[Doug MacLean]] on the [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] AM sports talk radio station [[The Fan 590]]. The show's name was later changed to ''The Game Plan''. In 2009, Doug MacLean left the show and was replaced by [[Eric Smith (sportscaster)|Eric Smith]].{{citation needed |date=June 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100208200538/http://www.tsn.ca/tsn_talent/bio/?id=11734 Bio from TSN.ca]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141213075221/http://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/coaches/jack-armstrong-1.html Jack Armstrong's NCAA coaching record on sports-reference.com]\n\n{{Niagara Purple Eagles men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armstrong, Jack}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Canada]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:American sports announcers]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Canadian bloggers]]\n[[Category:Canadian radio sportscasters]]\n[[Category:Canadian television sportscasters]]\n[[Category:College men's basketball head coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fordham University alumni]]\n[[Category:Niagara Purple Eagles men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:People from Lewiston, New York]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Toronto Raptors broadcasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Jack Armstrong\n| image = 1_matt_devlin_jack_armstrong_2019.jpg\n| caption = Armstrong (right) with [[Matt Devlin (sportscaster)|Matt Devlin]] at Game 2 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]\n| birth_name = John Joseph Armstrong\n| birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1963|1|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation = [[Sportscaster]]\n| networth = \n|alma_mater =[[Fordham University]]\n| employer = [[Bell Media]]\n| spouse = Dena Armstrong\n| children = Brian Armstrong, Kevin Armstrong, Tim Armstrong\n| website = \n}}\n'''John Joseph \"Jack\" Armstrong''' (born January 3, 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/coaches/jack-armstrong-1.html|title=Jack Armstrong Coaching Record - College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref> is an American[[sportscaster]], working primarily for the [[Toronto Raptors]] on [[The Sports Network|TSN]] and [[NBA TV Canada]]. Armstrong is also the college basketball analyst for [[The Sports Network|TSN]]. \n\n==Personal==\nJack is the son of Irish immigrants. He has three brothers, William, James and Brendan. Jack's father died when Jack was age seven and his mother Mary raised him alone.<ref name=\"tgm\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/article-raptors-broadcaster-jack-armstrong-father-to-three-adopted-sons/ |title=Raptors broadcaster Jack Armstrong, father to three adopted sons, calls parenting \u2018an amazing gift\u2019 |first=Lori |last=Ewing |date=October 15, 2018 |work=The Globe and Mail |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref> Armstrong graduated from [[Fordham University]] in 1985 with a Masters in Communication.<ref>{{cite web |work=Fordham Alumni |url=https://fordhamsports.com/news/2014/12/21/GEN_1221142243.aspx |title=Alumni RAMblings - Jack Armstrong |date=December 21, 2014 |accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJack is married to Dena Armstrong, who  was the women's soccer coach at Niagara University. They met at Niagara University, when they were both coaches. They are the parents of three adopted sons.<ref name=\"tgm\"/> They live in [[Lewiston, New York]] just across the Niagara River from Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/basketball/nba/20-questions-toronto-raptors-broadcaster-jack-armstrong-on-being-happy-the-all-consuming-stress-of-coaching-and-the-vince-carter-era |title=20 Questions: Toronto Raptors broadcaster Jack Armstrong on being happy, the 'all-consuming' stress of coaching and the Vince Carter era |date=January 8, 2015 |work=The National Post |accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nFrom 1989 to 1998, Armstrong was the lead basketball coach of [[Niagara University]]. In the 1992\u201393 season, he led the [[Niagara Purple Eagles men's basketball|Niagara Purple Eagles]] to a 23\u20137 record and was named the New York State Division I Coach of the Year. His overall record with the team was 100-154.<ref name=buff /> \n\n==Broadcast career==\nArmstrong is currently an NBA analyst for [[The Sports Network|TSN]] and the on-air in-game broadcaster for the [[Toronto Raptors]] NBA team.<ref name=\"tgm\"/> He has been a part of the broadcast team since 2000.<ref name=buff>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2015/07/17/jack-armstrong-is-going-strong-as-broadcast-analyst-for-the-toronto-raptors/|title=Jack Armstrong is going strong as broadcast analyst for the Toronto Raptors|date=July 17, 2015}}</ref> Armstrong has two catch-phrases that he uses during game broadcasts: \"Helloooo\" and \"Get that garbage outta here\".<ref name=\"tgm\"/> The \"get that garbage outta here\" phrase was also used by Armstrong in commercials for the [[City of Toronto government]] to encourage keeping garbage out of recycling materials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.ca/services-payments/recycling-organics-garbage/houses/what-goes-in-my-blue-bin/ |title=What Goes in the Blue Bin? |publisher=City of Toronto |accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nArmstrong is a 3 time winner of the [[Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] for Best Sports Analyst in a Sports Program or Series.\n\nOn Thursday, July 31, 2008, it was announced that Jack Armstrong would take over ''[[The Chuck Swirsky Show]]'' effective August 18, 2008, alongside [[Doug MacLean]] on the [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] AM sports talk radio station [[The Fan 590]]. The show's name was later changed to ''The Game Plan''. In 2009, Doug MacLean left the show and was replaced by [[Eric Smith (sportscaster)|Eric Smith]].{{citation needed |date=June 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100208200538/http://www.tsn.ca/tsn_talent/bio/?id=11734 Bio from TSN.ca]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141213075221/http://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/coaches/jack-armstrong-1.html Jack Armstrong's NCAA coaching record on sports-reference.com]\n\n{{Niagara Purple Eagles men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armstrong, Jack}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Canada]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:American sports announcers]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Canadian bloggers]]\n[[Category:Canadian radio sportscasters]]\n[[Category:Canadian television sportscasters]]\n[[Category:College men's basketball head coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fordham University alumni]]\n[[Category:Niagara Purple Eagles men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:People from Lewiston, New York]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Toronto Raptors broadcasters]]\n", "name_user": "Hockeypro2000", "label": "safe", "comme